concentration camps. In this rich, evocative account, James McAuley explores the central role that art and material culture played in the assimilation and identity of French Jews in the fin-de-siècle. Weaving together narratives of various figures, some familiar from the works of Marcel Proust and the diaries of Jules and Edmond Goncourt—the Camondos, the Rothschilds, the Ephrussis, the Cahens d'Anvers—McAuley shows how Jewish art collectors contended with a powerful strain of anti-Semitism: they were often accused of “invading” France’s cultural patrimony. The collections these families left behind—many ultimately donated to the French state—were their response, tragic attempts to celebrate a nation that later betrayed them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aAntisemitismzFrancexHistory. 0aArt and societyzFrancexHistory. 0aArtxCollectors and collectingxBiography. 0aArtxPrivate collectionszFrance. 0aArtxProtectionzFrancexHistory. 0aJewish artxPrivate collectionszFrance. 0aJewszFrancexSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aJewszFrancexSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConfiscations and contributionszFrance. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073923740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300252545423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97803002525